like finance reform.

00:44:28.070 --> 00:44:30.890
There's no way that we're going
to-- I mean, why would you

00:44:30.890 --> 00:44:33.460
convince your kids to follow
these values that I'm espousing

00:44:33.460 --> 00:44:35.880
if at the same time, Wall
Street can do a pretty

00:44:35.880 --> 00:44:38.890
much act like five year
olds anytime they want?

00:44:38.890 --> 00:44:41.930
So it's not like we're simply
building role models here.

00:44:41.930 --> 00:44:43.090
But it's important.

00:44:43.090 --> 00:44:45.130
It's absolutely important
beyond the damage that

00:44:45.130 --> 00:44:48.220
gets done to our economy and our
individual sense of security.

00:44:48.220 --> 00:44:51.720
So there are definitely
calls-- opportunities--

00:44:51.720 --> 00:44:56.550
for top down remedies in things
like finance reform, campaign

00:44:56.550 --> 00:44:57.320
finance reform.

00:44:57.320 --> 00:44:59.050
Since the entire
political sphere

00:44:59.050 --> 00:45:01.910
is in the capture of
this same-- I mean,

00:45:01.910 --> 00:45:04.330
there's so much
money in politics,

00:45:04.330 --> 00:45:06.650
it's essentially an arm
of the financial sector.

00:45:06.650 --> 00:45:09.367
So donors are really
thought of as investors.

00:45:09.367 --> 00:45:10.950
The amounts of money
they're investing

00:45:10.950 --> 00:45:13.480
are so large that they
expect a fast return.

00:45:13.480 --> 00:45:16.050
And the most efficient way
to deliver a fast return

00:45:16.050 --> 00:45:17.760
in politics is to go extreme.

00:45:17.760 --> 00:45:19.780
So you've just built
in this little feedback

00:45:19.780 --> 00:45:24.110
loop that creates
partisan gridlock.

00:45:24.110 --> 00:45:26.602
Campaign finance reform is
not the entire solution.

00:45:26.602 --> 00:45:27.560
But it's a piece of it.

00:45:27.560 --> 00:45:30.140
But I think that if-- and
this is a dream world,

00:45:30.140 --> 00:45:31.890
if I was put in
charge-- I would want

00:45:31.890 --> 00:45:33.710
to see these top down reforms.

00:45:33.710 --> 00:45:36.270
But I would also
want to see some way

00:45:36.270 --> 00:45:39.170
to help articulate and support
a grassroots movement where

00:45:39.170 --> 00:45:41.540
people individually are
pushing back and sending

00:45:41.540 --> 00:45:43.840
a message to the
politicians that the status

00:45:43.840 --> 00:45:45.530
quo doesn't work anymore.

00:45:45.530 --> 00:45:47.670
We're tired of losing
things that matter to us.

00:45:47.670 --> 00:45:49.450
So that we're not
having to wait until we

00:45:49.450 --> 00:45:51.380
go to rehab to
pull ourselves out.

00:45:51.380 --> 00:45:55.310
And meanwhile, our
kids are totally lost.

00:45:55.310 --> 00:45:56.560
So it has to be a combination.

00:45:56.560 --> 00:45:58.390
And I am far from having
it all worked out.

00:45:58.390 --> 00:45:58.890
Believe me.

00:45:58.890 --> 00:46:00.960
And I even know that.

00:46:00.960 --> 00:46:04.460
But I think we need to start
with this idea of pushing back.

00:46:04.460 --> 00:46:05.190
Creating space.

00:46:05.190 --> 00:46:07.273
And that space might be
filled from the bottom up.

00:46:07.273 --> 00:46:09.640
And it also might be
filled from the top down.

00:46:09.640 --> 00:46:12.500
I was actually looking
at the government

00:46:12.500 --> 00:46:13.820
shutdown as an opportunity.

00:46:13.820 --> 00:46:16.500
Because in the
aftermath, you have

00:46:16.500 --> 00:46:18.720
a lot of political leaders
sort of just going, whoa.

00:46:18.720 --> 00:46:20.020
You see what just happened?

00:46:20.020 --> 00:46:22.000
I mean, that was close.

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:25.620
And I think it caused
some to be willing to step

00:46:25.620 --> 00:46:27.550
back, and reconsider
some slightly

00:46:27.550 --> 00:46:29.950
older political criteria.

00:46:29.950 --> 00:46:31.450
I mean, they were
just as corrupt.

00:46:31.450 --> 00:46:33.900
But at least they were able
to get a few things done.

00:46:33.900 --> 00:46:38.630
And I suspect that there
is a hunger, an appetite,

00:46:38.630 --> 00:46:42.100
for more of that,
than one might have

00:46:42.100 --> 00:46:44.020
thought before two years ago.

00:46:44.020 --> 00:46:46.380
So I remain marginally hopeful.

00:46:46.380 --> 00:46:49.440
But absolutely we need a
combination of top down

00:46:49.440 --> 00:46:52.490
and bottom up
approaches to this.

00:46:52.490 --> 00:46:54.550
So thanks very much.

00:46:54.550 --> 00:46:57.690
Another question?

00:46:57.690 --> 00:47:02.630
-So I find it very interesting
that you brought up

00:47:02.630 --> 00:47:06.360
technological solutions to
some of the questions of power.

00:47:06.360 --> 00:47:11.640
How do we step back and
look at the implications

00:47:11.640 --> 00:47:14.660
of using certain kinds of power
the marketplace brings us,

00:47:14.660 --> 00:47:17.944
after talking about
Amazon Fire phone?

00:47:17.944 --> 00:47:19.360
Right, so the
interesting question

00:47:19.360 --> 00:47:24.180
here is, the technological
model today is all

00:47:24.180 --> 00:47:26.850
driven from the same
marketplace that you

00:47:26.850 --> 00:47:28.940
are kind of defending
yourself against.

00:47:28.940 --> 00:47:36.320
And I'm not sure how
to reconcile this.

00:47:36.320 --> 00:47:39.700
How can we, as
technologists, if we

00:47:39.700 --> 00:47:44.810
wanted to solve this or make an
incremental amount of progress

00:47:44.810 --> 00:47:49.690
toward solving this, how can
we-- even if we're meaning,

00:47:49.690 --> 00:47:52.420
convince the public
that we're not

00:47:52.420 --> 00:47:55.120
building another Amazon Fire.

00:47:55.120 --> 00:47:58.500
That the tool that
we're trying to provide

00:47:58.500 --> 00:48:02.730
to make it easier for
people to step back is not,

00:48:02.730 --> 00:48:04.940
in fact, skewed just
simply in our favor.

00:48:04.940 --> 00:48:08.600
I mean, this is the crux of
some of the arguments being made

00:48:08.600 --> 00:48:10.110
in Europe right
now, with respect

00:48:10.110 --> 00:48:13.960
to a lot of American
technological companies.

00:48:13.960 --> 00:48:22.360
Is that we don't respect some
of their traditions in the way.

00:48:22.360 --> 00:48:24.666
Like, right to be
forgotten, for example.

00:48:24.666 --> 00:48:26.040
Something that
they traditionally

00:48:26.040 --> 00:48:29.030
thought of as very important,
that level of privacy.

00:48:29.030 --> 00:48:30.550
And all of these
American companies

00:48:30.550 --> 00:48:32.670
coming in and just saying, nah.

00:48:32.670 --> 00:48:35.380
Doesn't matter.

00:48:35.380 --> 00:48:39.530
So do you have any
thoughts on how can we

00:48:39.530 --> 00:48:41.790
find that balance
slash regain the trust?

00:48:41.790 --> 00:48:46.230
Because it seems like we lost
it as a sector of the economy,

00:48:46.230 --> 00:48:47.214
if you will.

00:48:47.214 --> 00:48:49.380
-Right, and you're sort of
front and center of that.

00:48:49.380 --> 00:48:50.630
That's a really good question.

00:48:50.630 --> 00:48:53.820
I think part of what's
going on here is that--

00:48:53.820 --> 00:48:55.811
and I'll speak in gross
generalizations here,

00:48:55.811 --> 00:48:57.310
because it's a safe
thing to do when

00:48:57.310 --> 00:48:58.601
you're at a particular company.

00:48:58.601 --> 00:49:04.720
But essentially what we've
done since the '80s is

00:49:04.720 --> 00:49:07.870
we've basically said,
if it's efficient,

00:49:07.870 --> 00:49:11.627
if it will cut
costs, if it's legal

00:49:11.627 --> 00:49:13.460
and it adds to the
bottom line, we'll do it.

00:49:13.460 --> 00:49:15.660
And that is going
to be our guideline.

00:49:15.660 --> 00:49:18.390
And we'll hem and
haw around the edges

00:49:18.390 --> 00:49:20.140
with social
responsibility and we'll

00:49:20.140 --> 00:49:24.810
plant a tree for every share
we buy back, or whatever.

00:49:24.810 --> 00:49:26.474
But generally
speaking, we're going

00:49:26.474 --> 00:49:27.640
to be pursuing those things.

00:49:27.640 --> 00:49:31.210
And we're going to let the
market make the determination.

00:49:31.210 --> 00:49:32.070
And why wouldn't we?

00:49:32.070 --> 00:49:34.320
Because we are responsible
to our shareholders.

00:49:34.320 --> 00:49:35.550
That's always a thing.

00:49:35.550 --> 00:49:37.110
What can we do?

00:49:37.110 --> 00:49:41.500
And so you have to fiddle a bit
with that nexus, as they like

00:49:41.500 --> 00:49:44.760
to call it, between--
It's the agency theorem.

00:49:44.760 --> 00:49:47.230
It's like, who's really
running the show here?

00:49:47.230 --> 00:49:49.100
I mean, the shareholder
can kind of say,

00:49:49.100 --> 00:49:50.770
well I bought the shares
but it's not my fault.

00:49:50.770 --> 00:49:51.603
It's not my company.

00:49:51.603 --> 00:49:53.400
And the company is
saying well, this

00:49:53.400 --> 00:49:55.120
is all for the shareholders.

00:49:55.120 --> 00:49:57.760
So I think we need-- that's
where more top down work needs

00:49:57.760 --> 00:50:00.110
to come in and say,
well, for example.

00:50:00.110 --> 00:50:03.720
Let's see if we can reduce the
emphasis on quarterly earnings.

00:50:03.720 --> 00:50:04.680
So how do we do that?

00:50:04.680 --> 00:50:06.890
Well maybe we could
reduce-- make it

00:50:06.890 --> 00:50:11.770
more expensive, or more
awkward, to pay in shares.

00:50:11.770 --> 00:50:13.850
So we can reign
that in somewhat.

00:50:13.850 --> 00:50:17.000
Let's maybe make it illegal
again to do share buybacks.

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:19.080
I mean, it used to be
recognized for what it is.

00:50:19.080 --> 00:50:21.020
It's price manipulation.

00:50:21.020 --> 00:50:23.560
But we decided in the
'80s that it wasn't.

00:50:23.560 --> 00:50:25.980
Or if it was, it
was worth the cost.

00:50:25.980 --> 00:50:29.819
And parenthetically, there are
times when share buyback is

00:50:29.819 --> 00:50:31.110
absolutely defensible, I think.

00:50:31.110 --> 00:50:33.350
When you're being
threatened with a takeover.

00:50:33.350 --> 00:50:35.692
Or if there's
nothing to invest in.

00:50:35.692 --> 00:50:37.400
You've got a pile of
cash, and you simply

00:50:37.400 --> 00:50:39.060
can't find something
to invest in.

00:50:39.060 --> 00:50:42.650
But because we've linked share
buybacks with compensation,

00:50:42.650 --> 00:50:44.520
it's very difficult
to trust that.

00:50:44.520 --> 00:50:45.550
You talk about trust.

00:50:45.550 --> 00:50:47.760
It's very difficult to
believe that what's going on

00:50:47.760 --> 00:50:51.340
is in the actual interest
of the corporation,

00:50:51.340 --> 00:50:54.090
and not just the interest of
the wallet of the executive

00:50:54.090 --> 00:50:55.730
making the decision.

00:50:55.730 --> 00:50:58.510
So there are things
we can do there.

00:50:58.510 --> 00:51:00.750
But in terms of--
but really, I think

00:51:00.750 --> 00:51:02.530
it's a philosophical question.

00:51:02.530 --> 00:51:05.180
We're sort of hoping that
someone will come and impose

00:51:05.180 --> 00:51:06.700
a new algorithm, right?

00:51:06.700 --> 00:51:09.747
And it'll be what we used
to rely on the Church for.

00:51:09.747 --> 00:51:12.080
I mean, the church said, here
was good, and here is bad.

00:51:12.080 --> 00:51:14.371
And here's how you conduct
yourselves to get to heaven.

00:51:14.371 --> 00:51:16.920
And here's how you conduct
yourselves if you don't care.

00:51:16.920 --> 00:51:19.100
And that was pretty
black and white.

00:51:19.100 --> 00:51:20.994
And we have gotten rid of that.

00:51:20.994 --> 00:51:22.910
And that has been the
sort of the big struggle

00:51:22.910 --> 00:51:23.743
of the 20th century.

00:51:23.743 --> 00:51:26.310
It's, like, well, we'll have a
cultural replacement for that,

00:51:26.310 --> 00:51:26.809
right?

00:51:26.809 --> 00:51:29.309
And our decision on what that
cultural replacement would

00:51:29.309 --> 00:51:30.850
look like, at least
from the '80s on,

00:51:30.850 --> 00:51:32.070
was obviously the market.

00:51:32.070 --> 00:51:33.629
Because Adam Smith said.

00:51:33.629 --> 00:51:35.420
But Adam Smith also
said a few other things

00:51:35.420 --> 00:51:37.310
about the moral
imperative that had

00:51:37.310 --> 00:51:41.660
to accompany the free market and
in pursuit of individual self

00:51:41.660 --> 00:51:43.660
interest, for the
invisible hand to work.

00:51:43.660 --> 00:51:45.160
And that's sort
have been forgotten.

00:51:45.160 --> 00:51:47.060
It comes down to
individual decisions.

00:51:49.765 --> 00:51:51.640
I think a lot of times,
what individuals want

00:51:51.640 --> 00:51:53.020
is not to have to
worry about it.

00:51:53.020 --> 00:51:55.394
To be able to say to themselves,
if that button is there,

00:51:55.394 --> 00:51:56.530
I'm going to click it.

00:51:56.530 --> 00:51:58.090
And if it's there, it's fine.

00:51:58.090 --> 00:52:00.270
And that's really the extent
of my decision making.

00:52:00.270 --> 00:52:03.565
If I've got 450 horsepower under
the hood of my Dodge Viper--

00:52:03.565 --> 00:52:06.910
and if anyone has one, I'm
sorry, because they're cool--

00:52:06.910 --> 00:52:08.760
I'm going to use it.

00:52:08.760 --> 00:52:12.270
I was out in Las Vegas
doing some deep research

00:52:12.270 --> 00:52:12.900
for this story.

00:52:12.900 --> 00:52:13.970
And there's a
place where you can

00:52:13.970 --> 00:52:16.178
go rent pretty much anything
out there, to try it out

00:52:16.178 --> 00:52:16.960
for the weekend.

00:52:16.960 --> 00:52:18.530
And the Dodge Viper
is super popular.

00:52:18.530 --> 00:52:20.842
Like, half the cars get
wrecked in the parking lot,

00:52:20.842 --> 00:52:23.050
because the guy's like
[VROOM NOISE] you know, just--

00:52:23.050 --> 00:52:23.549
anyway.

00:52:23.549 --> 00:52:25.730
Just put that in your
pipe and smoke it.

00:52:25.730 --> 00:52:27.790
But it comes down
to individuals.

00:52:27.790 --> 00:52:30.765
And individuals make
decisions based on the culture

00:52:30.765 --> 00:52:32.240
that they're raised in.

00:52:32.240 --> 00:52:35.050
And I think we have to go back
to imposing a moral framework.

00:52:35.050 --> 00:52:37.330
And then the question is,
well, whose moral framework?

00:52:37.330 --> 00:52:39.600
But that's a debate
we don't want to have.

00:52:39.600 --> 00:52:42.089
We thought we'd eliminated
the need for that debate.

00:52:42.089 --> 00:52:44.130
Because we're going to
have the market handle it.

00:52:44.130 --> 00:52:46.200
And it turns out, no.

00:52:46.200 --> 00:52:47.890
It's a moral discussion
we need to have.

00:52:47.890 --> 00:52:50.302
And that's sort of what we're
on the cusp of, as well.

00:52:50.302 --> 00:52:52.260
And isn't necessarily
something that technology

00:52:52.260 --> 00:52:53.180
will help us in.

00:52:53.180 --> 00:52:54.710
But it's also
something technology

00:52:54.710 --> 00:52:56.560
doesn't need to
hinder us in, either.

00:52:56.560 --> 00:52:59.090
But it's still a
discussion we need to have.

00:52:59.090 --> 00:53:01.620
So I know that's an
unsatisfactory answer.

00:53:01.620 --> 00:53:03.780
But it's what I've got today.

00:53:03.780 --> 00:53:06.279
But thanks for the question.

00:53:06.279 --> 00:53:06.820
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:53:06.820 --> 00:53:09.970
It seems like we're
on the brink of having

00:53:09.970 --> 00:53:14.210
the capability for people
to design and have things

00:53:14.210 --> 00:53:17.120
fabricated to their
own specifications.

00:53:17.120 --> 00:53:18.760
And I'd just like to
hear your thoughts

00:53:18.760 --> 00:53:20.960
on how that's going to play out.

00:53:20.960 --> 00:53:23.210
PAUL ROBERTS: So
do you mean, like,

00:53:23.210 --> 00:53:24.710
3D printing, as an example?

00:53:24.710 --> 00:53:25.460
AUDIENCE: Exactly.

00:53:25.460 --> 00:53:27.335
PAUL ROBERTS: I mean,
this is a great example

00:53:27.335 --> 00:53:30.660
of the double-edged
nature of technology.

00:53:30.660 --> 00:53:34.300
I mean, the ability
to make what you need

00:53:34.300 --> 00:53:36.990
and not have to go somewhere
and waste all these resources.

00:53:36.990 --> 00:53:39.020
And to only make one
of them, as opposed

00:53:39.020 --> 00:53:42.570
to buying a three
pack at Costco.

00:53:42.570 --> 00:53:44.782
And maybe the extra
labor and thought

00:53:44.782 --> 00:53:47.240
that goes into making it at
home, even though it's supposed

00:53:47.240 --> 00:53:50.420
to be super easy, will
kind of reimpose this sense

00:53:50.420 --> 00:53:52.260
of deliberation on the decision.

00:53:52.260 --> 00:53:54.260
You know, now if you just
go in, and think well,

00:53:54.260 --> 00:53:57.360
jeez, I need a disposable razor.

00:53:57.360 --> 00:53:58.720
Oh look, there's a pack of 100.

00:53:58.720 --> 00:54:00.140
I'll get those.

00:54:00.140 --> 00:54:03.570
If you had to make each
razor, it's like, wow.

00:54:03.570 --> 00:54:06.420
I guess I can grow
a beard, you know.

00:54:06.420 --> 00:54:12.540
But I think that by bringing
back the act of production

00:54:12.540 --> 00:54:16.330
into individual life,
I think that can only

00:54:16.330 --> 00:54:17.370
have positive effects.

00:54:17.370 --> 00:54:22.260
Because we've really lost the
whole notion of production.

00:54:22.260 --> 00:54:24.109
That's why we call
ourselves consumers.

00:54:24.109 --> 00:54:25.150
We used to make a living.

00:54:25.150 --> 00:54:26.650
And now we just buy it.

00:54:26.650 --> 00:54:29.066
And by bringing that back in,
I think that could be great.

00:54:29.066 --> 00:54:31.010
I mean, clearly, if what
we're making is Uzis,

00:54:31.010 --> 00:54:35.080
then there's a problem.

00:54:35.080 --> 00:54:36.010
And that concerns me.

00:54:36.010 --> 00:54:38.210
But I don't think it's that.

00:54:38.210 --> 00:54:41.300
I think that issue will
have to be addressed along

00:54:41.300 --> 00:54:44.190
with the issue of other
potential abuses of all

00:54:44.190 --> 00:54:46.830
this technological capability
we're putting out there.

00:54:46.830 --> 00:54:50.030
So I'm actually pretty hopeful
specifically for this notion

00:54:50.030 --> 00:54:52.020
of bringing the
act of production

00:54:52.020 --> 00:54:55.077
back into the lives
of individuals.

00:54:55.077 --> 00:54:55.577
Thanks.

00:54:58.440 --> 00:55:01.670
AUDIENCE: If the
human conscience

00:55:01.670 --> 00:55:04.930
fails to counteract
the selfishness

00:55:04.930 --> 00:55:10.720
and the overwhelming ability
that it is not balanced out

00:55:10.720 --> 00:55:15.532
by responsibility, what does the
Orwellian nightmare look like?

00:55:15.532 --> 00:55:17.240
PAUL ROBERTS: Well,
I think it looks more

00:55:17.240 --> 00:55:18.920
like what we're
living in right now.

00:55:18.920 --> 00:55:24.121
I mean, it's definitely more
inequality because-- I mean,

00:55:24.121 --> 00:55:25.870
I want to blame
everything on Wall Street,

00:55:25.870 --> 00:55:26.840
but why not, you know?

00:55:26.840 --> 00:55:27.340
No.

00:55:27.340 --> 00:55:30.320
There's so much
capability in that sector.

00:55:30.320 --> 00:55:33.966
And it's being used in ways that
are not entirely pro-social.

00:55:33.966 --> 00:55:35.340
I think what we'll
end up looking

00:55:35.340 --> 00:55:38.160
at is a more in-egalitarian
society-- one that

00:55:38.160 --> 00:55:40.710
has a smaller and
smaller middle class.

00:55:40.710 --> 00:55:47.600
Because all the ways we sort
of propped up the middle class,

00:55:47.600 --> 00:55:50.110
and the circumstances that
allowed the middle class

00:55:50.110 --> 00:55:52.029
to flow, we're not
interested in restoring,

00:55:52.029 --> 00:55:53.570
in a society that's
solely interested

00:55:53.570 --> 00:55:55.215
in instant gratification.

00:55:55.215 --> 00:55:58.080
You know, Tyler Cowen, his
book "The End of Average"--

00:55:58.080 --> 00:56:02.740
I think he paints a pretty
plausible picture for what

00:56:02.740 --> 00:56:04.750
such a society would look like.

00:56:04.750 --> 00:56:07.350
And then once you've split
a society so effectively

00:56:07.350 --> 00:56:10.770
between those in the top, the
expert class, and everyone

00:56:10.770 --> 00:56:13.950
else, then democracy
becomes, in fact, a joke.

00:56:13.950 --> 00:56:17.040
Because why would
you politically

00:56:17.040 --> 00:56:18.710
buy into a situation like that?

00:56:18.710 --> 00:56:21.140
And once democracy is a
joke-- or I should say,

00:56:21.140 --> 00:56:24.010
more of a joke than it already
is-- then everything sort of

00:56:24.010 --> 00:56:24.990
falls apart.

00:56:24.990 --> 00:56:28.650
And because we've
developed this capacity

00:56:28.650 --> 00:56:30.790
for incremental change,
and change that's

00:56:30.790 --> 00:56:35.410
so massive and yet so
hard to detect sometimes,

00:56:35.410 --> 00:56:38.260
all this could have happened,
like, last year, already.

00:56:38.260 --> 00:56:40.149
I mean, I might
not even be here.

00:56:40.149 --> 00:56:42.690
It's just one of those things
where you realize-- seriously--

00:56:42.690 --> 00:56:46.320
that so much of this stuff
is already under way.

00:56:46.320 --> 00:56:50.720
And I think when I'm
being really paranoid--

00:56:50.720 --> 00:56:54.126
and I come from Washington
state, where pot is now legal.

00:56:54.126 --> 00:56:55.500
When I'm being
really paranoid, I

00:56:55.500 --> 00:57:00.690
sort of think that we're
past the point where

00:57:00.690 --> 00:57:02.936
we can make a difference.

00:57:02.936 --> 00:57:04.310
And in part, we're
past the point

00:57:04.310 --> 00:57:08.450
because we're so accustomed
to having what we want now

00:57:08.450 --> 00:57:12.920
that the idea of systematically
delaying gratification

00:57:12.920 --> 00:57:15.140
is beyond our capacity.

00:57:15.140 --> 00:57:20.240
Now, it may be done for us,
when systems break down.

00:57:20.240 --> 00:57:24.490
But maybe the worst nightmare is
that we sort of continue along

00:57:24.490 --> 00:57:27.880
well enough to sort of keep
the cloak in front of our eyes.

00:57:27.880 --> 00:57:30.250
So that's, you know,
when I'm feeling

00:57:30.250 --> 00:57:32.240
super paranoid and pessimistic.

00:57:32.240 --> 00:57:36.540
On the other hand, when I see
people in my own community

00:57:36.540 --> 00:57:41.900
who are stepping back and like,
quitting a high-powered Wall

00:57:41.900 --> 00:57:43.280
Street job to become a teacher.

00:57:43.280 --> 00:57:44.050
I love these stories.

00:57:44.050 --> 00:57:45.758
I mean, I'm reading
them on the internet.

00:57:45.758 --> 00:57:47.340
And actually, I cry every time.

00:57:47.340 --> 00:57:49.250
Because it's corny.

00:57:49.250 --> 00:57:50.920
But I mean, the idea
that someone says,

00:57:50.920 --> 00:57:53.357
ugh, this thing
isn't working for me,

00:57:53.357 --> 00:57:54.940
even though I'm
making a lot of money.

00:57:54.940 --> 00:57:56.820
It's stressful and
it feels wrong.

00:57:56.820 --> 00:57:59.310
And then they end up teaching
math in an inner city.

00:57:59.310 --> 00:58:02.000
And you know, maybe it
doesn't last forever.

00:58:02.000 --> 00:58:04.550
But I mean, that
potential is there.

00:58:04.550 --> 00:58:07.635
That sort of
individual capability

00:58:07.635 --> 00:58:09.760
and individual willingness
to think beyond the self

00:58:09.760 --> 00:58:10.384
is still there.

00:58:10.384 --> 00:58:12.170
And I guess that's
what gives me hope.

00:58:12.170 --> 00:58:14.480
So, yeah, thanks.

00:58:14.480 --> 00:58:15.980
AUDIENCE: A lot of
what you describe

00:58:15.980 --> 00:58:18.100
is just technological
progress to me.

00:58:18.100 --> 00:58:20.870
You know, if showrooming
eliminates showrooms,

00:58:20.870 --> 00:58:23.985
I guess it's just like
trains eliminated coaches.

00:58:23.985 --> 00:58:28.180
And maybe cars
diminished the role

00:58:28.180 --> 00:58:30.020
of trains in individual
transportation.

00:58:30.020 --> 00:58:33.710
That's [INAUDIBLE] of
many examples out there.

00:58:33.710 --> 00:58:35.044
So I'm not so concerned.

00:58:35.044 --> 00:58:36.710
I mean, maybe concerned
about, you know,

00:58:36.710 --> 00:58:38.904
that's just the way
things have been.

00:58:38.904 --> 00:58:41.070
What about-- but there's
something bigger, I think--

00:58:41.070 --> 00:58:44.720
and that's-- you and me simply
had some conversation over

00:58:44.720 --> 00:58:50.060
lunch-- what about
optimization of jobs?

00:58:50.060 --> 00:58:54.190
That robots not only replace
many manufacturing jobs,

00:58:54.190 --> 00:58:59.180
but many other jobs--
white collar jobs.

00:58:59.180 --> 00:59:03.712
The biggest social question I
see, and I kind of worry-- I

00:59:03.712 --> 00:59:06.170
don't know if it's the question
of next five years or maybe

00:59:06.170 --> 00:59:07.394
next 20 years.

00:59:07.394 --> 00:59:08.852
But I think it's
a question we have

00:59:08.852 --> 00:59:13.740
to face soon is there will
be no jobs for people.

00:59:13.740 --> 00:59:15.052
And we're done.

00:59:15.052 --> 00:59:17.020
What are your thoughts?

00:59:17.020 --> 00:59:17.360
PAUL ROBERTS: Well,
that's all the time we've

00:59:17.360 --> 00:59:18.867
got for questions
today. (LAUGHS)

00:59:18.867 --> 00:59:20.060
[LAUGHTER]

00:59:20.060 --> 00:59:22.700
Yeah, I mean, that's sort of
the 64 trillion question, right?

00:59:22.700 --> 00:59:24.658
It's like, well, so this
automation has kind of

00:59:24.658 --> 00:59:25.850
gone past the assembly line.

00:59:25.850 --> 00:59:27.760
It's now moving into
the white collar.

00:59:27.760 --> 00:59:30.160
Half the sports stories
you read on the wire

00:59:30.160 --> 00:59:31.990
are all done by robot.

00:59:31.990 --> 00:59:34.840
And not that you'd know.

00:59:34.840 --> 00:59:37.680
And lawyers-- I mean, the
whole legal profession

00:59:37.680 --> 00:59:40.310
is just being turned inside
out by these algorithms that

00:59:40.310 --> 00:59:41.979
can do-- And so
yes, it's happening.

00:59:41.979 --> 00:59:43.770
And I think you raise
an interesting point.

00:59:43.770 --> 00:59:45.570
Because you made
initially the point

00:59:45.570 --> 00:59:47.600
that well, we didn't
worry too much

00:59:47.600 --> 00:59:51.980
about when cars replaced
horse and buggy, right?

00:59:51.980 --> 00:59:53.820
And that's just sort
of the way things go.

00:59:53.820 --> 00:59:55.670
But think what cars brought.

00:59:55.670 --> 00:59:57.820
The car was part
of a much larger,

00:59:57.820 --> 01:00:00.650
massive multi-phase
Industrial Revolution that

01:00:00.650 --> 01:00:02.400
included not just cars
and transportation,

01:00:02.400 --> 01:00:04.316
but included all the
ancillary industries that

01:00:04.316 --> 01:00:05.290
had to feed into cars.

01:00:05.290 --> 01:00:06.716
So it was like,
tires, and steel.

01:00:06.716 --> 01:00:08.090
And all the
engineering expertise

01:00:08.090 --> 01:00:08.950
that had to go into that.

01:00:08.950 --> 01:00:11.033
And the petrochemical
business, and road building.

01:00:11.033 --> 01:00:13.917
So you have all these massive
multiplier effects going along.

01:00:13.917 --> 01:00:15.500
And in many of these
sectors, the jobs

01:00:15.500 --> 01:00:18.340
were higher paying than they
had been in the horse and buggy.

01:00:18.340 --> 01:00:20.220
So you have this
massive explosion.

01:00:20.220 --> 01:00:23.670
A lot of destruction, but
a lot of creation, as well.

01:00:23.670 --> 01:00:27.490
We have not seen that happen
in the automation revolution,

01:00:27.490 --> 01:00:29.450
as you point out.

01:00:29.450 --> 01:00:31.390
We're coming up with new jobs.

01:00:31.390 --> 01:00:34.830
But they don't replace the
jobs in terms of wages,

01:00:34.830 --> 01:00:35.521
by any means.

01:00:35.521 --> 01:00:37.270
I know you've heard
this statistic before,

01:00:37.270 --> 01:00:46.000
but 60% of the jobs that
were lost in the recession

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:47.946
were mid wage jobs.

01:00:47.946 --> 01:00:49.570
And 60% of the ones
that have come back

01:00:49.570 --> 01:00:50.742
are service, are low wage.

01:00:50.742 --> 01:00:52.450
And you know, people
keep thinking, well,

01:00:52.450 --> 01:00:53.841
that's just an anomaly.

01:00:53.841 --> 01:00:54.840
Things are going around.

01:00:54.840 --> 01:00:56.096
It's like-- oh, well.

01:00:56.096 --> 01:00:58.220
And it's really making it
tough for a lot of people

01:00:58.220 --> 01:01:01.050
who have always supported
creative destruction

01:01:01.050 --> 01:01:03.610
as this thing that's
worth the pain.

01:01:03.610 --> 01:01:06.060
And that argument is
getting-- I mean, who knows?

01:01:06.060 --> 01:01:07.310
Maybe things will turn around.

01:01:07.310 --> 01:01:11.360
Maybe that pattern will
return to the mean.

01:01:11.360 --> 01:01:12.510
But maybe not.

01:01:12.510 --> 01:01:14.410
And then we have a
real question to ask.

01:01:14.410 --> 01:01:16.410
So is the answer basic income?

01:01:16.410 --> 01:01:18.370
Do we just acknowledge
that we've lost,

01:01:18.370 --> 01:01:21.230
and let's just start
taxing the rich even more,

01:01:21.230 --> 01:01:23.000
and creating a basic income?

01:01:23.000 --> 01:01:26.116
And then, OK, so that allows
a certain level of security

01:01:26.116 --> 01:01:26.990
that people can feel.

01:01:26.990 --> 01:01:28.630
And maybe that level
of security allows

01:01:28.630 --> 01:01:30.275
them to be more civic minded.

01:01:30.275 --> 01:01:30.900
So that's good.

01:01:30.900 --> 01:01:32.310
But then what about
the incentives

01:01:32.310 --> 01:01:33.684
for giving people
a basic income?

01:01:33.684 --> 01:01:35.760
What does that do to
their willingness to work?

01:01:35.760 --> 01:01:39.410
And so, I mean,
it's really tough.

01:01:39.410 --> 01:01:41.030
And at the end of
the day, there's

01:01:41.030 --> 01:01:44.300
no constitutional guarantee
that we get through this mess.

01:01:44.300 --> 01:01:48.110
I think we've come through
so many things in the past.

01:01:48.110 --> 01:01:50.990
And we've conquered some pretty
complex challenges in the past.

01:01:50.990 --> 01:01:52.440
And we've done so collectively.

01:01:52.440 --> 01:01:55.380
And I think that's what
gives us the optimism.

01:01:55.380 --> 01:01:57.589
And we know what
the worst case is.

01:01:57.589 --> 01:01:59.880
We're sort of talking, we're
describing the worst case.

01:01:59.880 --> 01:02:01.421
And what I'm interested
in is, what's

01:02:01.421 --> 01:02:05.080
the next step away
from the worst case?

01:02:05.080 --> 01:02:07.670
Now that's the thing I want
to focus on, because I mean,

01:02:07.670 --> 01:02:09.520
I sort of grew up
professionally covering

01:02:09.520 --> 01:02:11.470
the environmental movement.

01:02:11.470 --> 01:02:14.776
And you have not met a bunch
of gloomier, grumpier people

01:02:14.776 --> 01:02:15.900
than the environmentalists.

01:02:15.900 --> 01:02:18.420
It's just like, geeze
Louise, you guys.

01:02:18.420 --> 01:02:22.182
I mean, I get that the world is
ending, but come on, you know?

01:02:22.182 --> 01:02:24.140
And then you go talk to
the business community,

01:02:24.140 --> 01:02:25.800
and they're like-- that's
where all the optimists are.

01:02:25.800 --> 01:02:27.170
They're all like,
yeah, this is great.

01:02:27.170 --> 01:02:29.477
And you realize, you've got
to have some combination.

01:02:29.477 --> 01:02:31.560
You've got to have that
energy of the marketplace.

01:02:31.560 --> 01:02:34.310
And I know-- ah, gee,
I should slap myself

01:02:34.310 --> 01:02:35.780
for being so cliche,
but I mean, it

01:02:35.780 --> 01:02:39.170
has to be a solution that
involves the market, you know?

01:02:39.170 --> 01:02:43.364
But we omitted ourselves
as the decision makers

01:02:43.364 --> 01:02:45.280
for so long, because we
basically said, oh, we

01:02:45.280 --> 01:02:46.821
don't have to have
a moral framework.

01:02:46.821 --> 01:02:47.740
This is so great.

01:02:47.740 --> 01:02:50.190
It's just a vacation
all the time.

01:02:50.190 --> 01:02:51.290
And it isn't the case.

01:02:51.290 --> 01:02:52.290
That's got to come back.

01:02:52.290 --> 01:02:54.030
So we have to make
decisions about,

01:02:54.030 --> 01:02:56.010
how much are we willing
to pay for food?

01:02:56.010 --> 01:02:57.030
Because it turns
out, if we follow

01:02:57.030 --> 01:02:58.880
that trend toward
automation and outsourcing,

01:02:58.880 --> 01:03:00.296
well, we can get
food super cheap.

01:03:00.296 --> 01:03:04.000
And we'll have truckloads
of beef for like, $0.99.

01:03:04.000 --> 01:03:06.530
But the cost to the economy,
and to the job market,

01:03:06.530 --> 01:03:11.500
and to society, and our civic
fabric will be intolerable.

01:03:11.500 --> 01:03:14.830
So that's why I like
the local food movement

01:03:14.830 --> 01:03:16.750
as a way to consider this.

01:03:16.750 --> 01:03:18.710
Because it forces you
to kind of go, wow.

01:03:18.710 --> 01:03:20.230
This food is good.

01:03:20.230 --> 01:03:21.490
And it's fresh.

01:03:21.490 --> 01:03:22.800
And I can see the producer.

01:03:22.800 --> 01:03:25.700
And I realize that
it involves work.

01:03:25.700 --> 01:03:27.590
And it involves a
person doing this work.

01:03:27.590 --> 01:03:30.930
And OK, it makes sense.

01:03:30.930 --> 01:03:35.530
I at least have some insight as
to why food should cost more.

01:03:35.530 --> 01:03:37.680
Is that the way to
reorient society?

01:03:37.680 --> 01:03:38.290
I doubt it.

01:03:38.290 --> 01:03:40.590
But I mean, it offers us a clue.

01:03:40.590 --> 01:03:42.799
So anyway, that's my two bits.

01:03:42.799 --> 01:03:43.840
Or actually my four bits.

01:03:43.840 --> 01:03:45.689
It's special today.

01:03:45.689 --> 01:03:46.675
Any other questions?

01:03:52.098 --> 01:03:55.056
AUDIENCE: Over the
last couple of decades,

01:03:55.056 --> 01:04:02.740
this civilization has been
willing to throw bombs

01:04:02.740 --> 01:04:05.100
in order to spread itself.

01:04:05.100 --> 01:04:06.770
I'm making it very provocative.

01:04:06.770 --> 01:04:11.836
But in light of what
you are discovering,

01:04:11.836 --> 01:04:14.210
does it shed doubt that we
have the moral right to do so?

01:04:14.210 --> 01:04:18.890
And maybe their
ways might actually

01:04:18.890 --> 01:04:23.030
be not inferior in
some certain respects?

01:04:23.030 --> 01:04:25.874
PAUL ROBERTS: Now, whose way?

01:04:25.874 --> 01:04:28.290
AUDIENCE: Well, I'm talking
about the Western civilization

01:04:28.290 --> 01:04:30.500
that we're all embedded in.

01:04:30.500 --> 01:04:34.730
And I'm talking about the
turmoil in the Middle East

01:04:34.730 --> 01:04:35.880
and so on.

01:04:35.880 --> 01:04:36.975
So--

01:04:36.975 --> 01:04:38.100
PAUL ROBERTS: You mean so--

01:04:38.100 --> 01:04:40.308
AUDIENCE: There are countries
and societies out there

01:04:40.308 --> 01:04:42.060
that violently
and aggressively--

01:04:42.060 --> 01:04:48.150
and energetically oppose our
ways of liberty and that.

01:04:48.150 --> 01:04:55.290
And sometimes those oppositions
end up being armed conflicts.

01:04:55.290 --> 01:05:01.300
And the narrative behind that
is Enduring Freedom-- the catch

01:05:01.300 --> 01:05:04.047
phrase.

01:05:04.047 --> 01:05:04.880
Is that still right?

01:05:07.382 --> 01:05:08.840
PAUL ROBERTS: I
mean, well, one way

01:05:08.840 --> 01:05:10.920
to answer that would
be to sort of ask,

01:05:10.920 --> 01:05:14.790
what of these traditional
value sets is worth preserving?

01:05:14.790 --> 01:05:19.950
And is our privilege to select?

01:05:19.950 --> 01:05:22.677
And I think, in any society
that's in a tumultuous stage

01:05:22.677 --> 01:05:24.760
like we are right now,
there's always the instinct

01:05:24.760 --> 01:05:26.862
to reach back for more
conservative-- I mean,

01:05:26.862 --> 01:05:28.570
that's the whole notion
of reactionaries.

01:05:28.570 --> 01:05:29.750
I mean, that's what happens.

01:05:29.750 --> 01:05:32.340
It's a potentially
dangerous time.

01:05:32.340 --> 01:05:34.580
But you look back--
I'll just use

01:05:34.580 --> 01:05:37.539
a mundane example
of the Victorians

01:05:37.539 --> 01:05:39.580
and how they dealt with
subjects that were taboo.

01:05:39.580 --> 01:05:42.080
I mean, you never discussed
politics or religion

01:05:42.080 --> 01:05:43.150
at the dinner table.

01:05:43.150 --> 01:05:45.410
And you do that because
you avoided arguments.

01:05:45.410 --> 01:05:48.060
And you allowed other
sort of social engagement

01:05:48.060 --> 01:05:49.830
to go forward.

01:05:49.830 --> 01:05:53.510
And, you know, I don't know
that the Victorians had

01:05:53.510 --> 01:05:56.080
the answer to everything,
or even a few things.

01:05:56.080 --> 01:05:59.260
But they did have a
few things figured out.

01:05:59.260 --> 01:06:00.860
And you look at
the way that we're

01:06:00.860 --> 01:06:03.199
so willing to share
anything with a stranger.

01:06:03.199 --> 01:06:04.740
I mean, you sit down
on a plane, it's

01:06:04.740 --> 01:06:08.059
like, wow, at the end of a
45 minute flight-- you know,

01:06:08.059 --> 01:06:09.850
(SILLY VOICE) "I'll
promise I'll write you.

01:06:09.850 --> 01:06:13.100
We're best buds now."

01:06:13.100 --> 01:06:15.510
Some things, I think,
should be withheld.

01:06:15.510 --> 01:06:17.600
That's just-- I'm 53 years
old and sort of coming

01:06:17.600 --> 01:06:18.989
to that conclusion, finally.

01:06:18.989 --> 01:06:21.280
And maybe there is something
to these older traditions.

01:06:21.280 --> 01:06:24.950
But I think you can't run
to them as total solutions.

01:06:24.950 --> 01:06:26.680
You have to understand
what they offer.

01:06:26.680 --> 01:06:28.744
And what the costs
and benefits are.

01:06:28.744 --> 01:06:30.160
You know, we're
sort of wishing we

01:06:30.160 --> 01:06:31.740
had this-- like,
you buy a house.

01:06:31.740 --> 01:06:33.340
You lock in your
30-year mortgage.

01:06:33.340 --> 01:06:34.881
And you don't have
to worry about it.

01:06:34.881 --> 01:06:37.190
And there's no analog here.

01:06:37.190 --> 01:06:39.250
We're going to have
be fighting over this

01:06:39.250 --> 01:06:40.830
and debating this forever.

01:06:40.830 --> 01:06:44.580
And this tension between the
individual and the collective

01:06:44.580 --> 01:06:45.552
is inherent.

01:06:45.552 --> 01:06:46.510
And will never go away.

01:06:46.510 --> 01:06:48.319
And if it did, that
would be scary.

01:06:48.319 --> 01:06:49.860
So it's a battle
we're going to have.

01:06:49.860 --> 01:06:52.060
And you guys are sort
of front and center.

01:06:52.060 --> 01:06:56.580
So thank you very much for the
attention and the questions.

01:06:56.580 --> 01:06:59.400
And all the best with
everything you're doing.

01:06:59.400 --> 01:07:00.950
Thanks.

